===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} [[martyr#Latin|martyr]] < {{etyl|grc|en}} '''{{polytonic|[[μάρτυρ]]}}''' (martyr), later form of '''{{polytonic|[[μάρτυς]]}}''' (martys) "witness".

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-martyr.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ɑː(r)tə(r)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# One who takes action according to his religious beliefs accepting that he will be killed by others; one who is put to death for his religion.
#: ''Stephen was the first Christian '''martyr'''''.
<!-- maybe somebody can find a way to include women without twice using "he or she"? -->
# Hence, one who sacrifices his life, his station, or what is of great value to him, for the sake of principle or to sustain a cause.
# (with a prepositional phrase of cause) One who suffers greatly.
#: ''Stephen was a '''martyr''' to arthritis.

